Throughout my life, Christmas would trigger sad emotions. I wasn’t fully aware or able to accept certain realities about my past, so I would push this aside and chalk it up to hormones. Yet, as the years went on and my path to inner healing continued, I recognized the seeds of sadness that were planted in my heart as a child. I don’t think these seeds were carefully placed, in fact, I don’t think it was intentional at all, but they were there. It lingered in the minor notes, woven into a song of longing and heartache.

6 years ago, in a house overlooking the Pacific Ocean, I was trying to still get over the trauma of resuscitating my little girl from SIDS. It was the month of December in Malibu, and I was taking time away to find healing from a slow unravel. The voice of Judy Garland began to sing “Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas” and the tears started to fall. Suddenly the unhealed wounds of a girl who lost her younger brother to cancer flooded my face.  There was a remembering that happened when Frankie’s body laid in my arms without life or movement. 

Christmas always affected me. I could remember my mother weeping as she prepared for another Christmas without her son and recalled her own childhood of disappointment. There were a handful of Christmases that as the last present was opened, she was already taking the ornaments off the tree to then have the Christmas tree barren in our front yard by noon. 

How do I wrap up these thoughts in 2200 characters? I don’t know. However, I know this... There could be a time where the minor notes wash over me, and I feel the wave of grief that only Christmas can reach. I can allow the visions of “normal” families remind me of the brokenness of my own. But as I gently and carefully handle the emotions that arise within me, I can choose to create an atmosphere for joy to be the seeds in which I plant into my family’s heart. A time where I notice those emotions, but I linger in delight as the tree remains lit for weeks to follow. A season that inevitably allows reflection, but gives birth to new hope that diverts attention from ourselves, to an overflow of giving that is the balm to heal, and peace that sustains.

Name it and claim it. I guess some would label it manifesting. I grew up with this mentality as I attended various non-denominational churches in SoCal. There was good in this, I must admit. I think hope is revolutionary and without it, things can be dreary and depressive. I walked through an early mid-life crisis in the last couple years and the hardest part was that I couldn’t see hope in myself. I also didn’t feel like I was living out my purpose. This wrecked me. 

I think I am the most excited about this coming year than I’ve been about years passed. Not because I think it will be the year of elaborate breakthrough…. not that it couldn’t be. But I believe it to be the year of tending to this beautiful new piece of land that is in my heart. 

I will forever be the believer of name and claim it, reach out and grab it, speak it into existence. It’s in my DNA. But the year of the breakthrough doesn’t have to look like a destination arrival. In redefining what breakthrough is, I believe that the seeds of ideas, the soil of creativity, and the tilling of strategy, are the foundation of hope and the landscape of dreams realized. 

Like my beloved blackberries take a handful of years to go from a seed to a delicious berry full of antioxidants (that ALTER how your brain neurons communicate…wild), I truly believe that this next season is hope planted. And it may take years to live in abundance off of this new land….but I know now that breaking ground IS truly the breakthrough. We don’t have to see a dream realized for it to be fully set in motion. With hopeful expectancy, I know that even if it takes 3 years to see the first signs of fruit, it’s coming. I know it’s coming. 

How many years I wasted in sadness discounting the miracles of the seeds. Believing only in the excitement of the harvest without the mindfulness of the hope in waiting. As I come out of a dark season and start to see my purpose unfolding anew, I can take joy in the journey as my hands once again find hope in the ground. 

📸: Ashtin Paige

The journey back to creating.
I’m gonna go out on a limb and share with you some thoughts I’ve had this week while talking with fellow creators. People are tired and losing faith in themselves. Don’t give up.

The thoughts of today circle around the emptiness of success. I’ve rarely seen artists experience a win and let it sustain them for a while. It easily becomes about the next big moment. Not that it is all bad! It’s a motivational factor for many of us to continue in a business that is the hardest (in my humble opinion) avenue to choose in all the options of work…But if a valley in your career makes you not experience joy, you will one day have the harsh realization that there were many other ways to achieve true happiness. 

Personal note: I don’t chase algorithms as many of you know. I’m not an intentional influencer by any means. The topics of this week are transpiring because of true inspiration in this moment. I’m grateful this is resonating with some of you as it has been wonderful to read your comments and share in the experience.

It’s crazy how much I love the 21 year old girl in this picture now. 

At the time it was taken, I felt like a massive failure. About ready to lose a second record deal, foreclose on my first house, have my car repossessed, go through my first divorce, and endure the mental anguish of leaving a guy with multiple arrests… yet still feeling like I was letting down “the church.” And the crazy part is, all of that didn’t scratch the surface of what was around the corner.

I admire her because she showed up in every situation with joy in her heart and found humor in the wildest of circumstances.

There was a period that I lived in a trailer with 10 people. My manager sent a couple dozen roses for my birthday, and I put them on the coffee table in the living room I was staying in with my 2 kids. I looked at the beautiful flowers and thought, that must’ve cost at least 150 dollars, I could really use that for groceries right about now!

The time I spent counting quarters, watching Disneyland fireworks outside of the park for free, rationing meals, celebrating every victory, became some of the sweetest times in my life. 

Hard times can last a while, but many times, they can end up just being a season. If we let the fear of the outcome take hold, we can miss out on living with joy. I am beyond grateful that when I had only a small handful of cash to live on, that I didn’t sit in a room and freeze. Instead, I dreamed bigger dreams, did whatever I could to keep my kids laughing and having fun, and can look back with such fondness for the sweet memories. Not that I didn’t have my punch the wall and kick a tire moments! 

What I’m trying to say is, whatever situation you’re in will eventually pass. Getting to the other side is important, but don’t let focusing on where you want to be, keep you from living today to the fullest. The struggle you’re in, may just end up being the most profound and life-changing moment in your life. The time where you’re fully aware and humbled enough to see the sweetest blessings and little miracles. Life on the way to your goals, matters more than being on the other side. There is joy in the struggle, so don’t miss out on it.

Maybe it was being a single mother so long?

Maybe from being in survival mode most of my life? 

But when I met this man, I was wound tightly. 

I’ve learned that in conflict, I like to say something and cut right through the center, while he likes to ponder, reflect, circle around, and circle back again. It has at times made me quite crazy. 

If Ryan has ever made you mad, I can promise that 99% of the time, he didn’t mean to do it. He just doesn’t have a bone in his body to hurt anyone. His intentions are just purely good. 

If you meet him and feel purity oozing from his being, it is 100% who he is. A champion of people and their art, even when it wasn’t returned. And they suck for that. (Ha! This is why I need him to smooth my edges.) 

He was before his time. He loved and accepted all people against all odds. He stood outside of the religious box, as he always knew God reached him in ways that were always outside of the box. 

He’s naturally wild. A man who can walk on the edge. He will get up at 5am to pray for you and meditate, but if injustice is done, you will set him off and he could just throw a big gulp at your car. (real story from his younger years) 

As a man with a business degree, and a bible theology degree (I think that’s what you call his bible stuff), he has these hidden gems of wisdom that are tucked within his layers of being a true-genuine-bonafide-distracted-artist. If you give him space to talk, he will drop the most profound wisdom. If you don’t give him space, he won’t force himself into it. 

It’s his Birthday today and I’m very grateful for him. He has taught me how to be a nurturer when it was so hard for me. He is teaching me how to hold my tongue, because that is also hard for me. When we met, he made me believe in God again when I didn’t know if I ever could. He is the truest of true. The friend who will do anything for you, except maybe call you back. The guy who would lay down his life for you, if you can just find him. A man of contradictions, talent beyond his knowledge, brilliant creativity, sensitivity into his depth, and strength to lead armies. Anyone who knows you, is better because of you…unless they suck.

I’d say we favor each other a bit?

Since he was a little guy with his dark hair and big eyes, I never got used to saying goodbye. The story of our relationship has been one mixed with anticipation and the sorrow of once again parting. 

As time goes, the gap gets smaller and the joy lasts longer. We weathered the storms of bi-coastal co-parenting and all that comes with the changes that happen after a divorce. 

And here we are…thriving, loving, experiencing more than we ever have, being continually grateful for our story and all the turns that it came with. 

And both of us now would say, all things came together for good. 

Until next time, my son! ❤️

Cause life is messy

For a while I’ve kept my pages mostly about work endeavors and some stories, never really digging in too deep on all sides of our life. 

For the last year, things have shifted dramatically as our hearts feel more called into the directions that matter to us and bring us the most life. 

We spent the last month traveling around and being a part of a conference in Georgia, with some of our dear friends. Frankie was baptized and we just had some of the most fulfilling moments we’ve experienced in quite some time. 

I won’t share everything right now, but I am very excited about what is unfolding in the next season. We are expanding our dreams as we open our time and hearts. We are discussing opportunities to share our stories to people through speaking and music, and it feels right. 

It’s crazy how you have so much collected inside and then one day, it’s just time. Time to start talking, time to start doing, time to use the stories for good. 

📸: @russcaitlynfender

As some of you have noticed, some things have been changing over here in my Insta-land. With the shifts of being more outspoken, you can start to lose followers, but it also replaces itself with people who appreciate the new content and who I am. 

So, I’d like to introduce myself to all my new Insta-friends! Here are 10 facts: 

1: I was born and raised in Corona, California. I won a singing contest through a local Christian radio station when I was 13. Through this, I made an indie project that landed me a record deal in Nashville when I was 15. 

2: After losing my Christian music career due to teenage pregnancy, I supported my daughter and I by singing demos in Nashville for top songwriters, which led me to traveling as a background singer for recording artists. 

3: By the time I was 25, I had two kids and two divorces, so I decided to move to L.A. to try and break out in the music industry.

4: I signed a deal with Warner Bros records and started to write music that landed on commercial spots and shows like, Ford, Victoria’s Secret, Orange is the New Black, Entourage, Californication, and many others. 

5: During this time, I was hired to start singing vocals for tv shows and movies like GLEE, American Horror Story, Hidden figures, The Goldberg’s, The Grinch Movie, etc.

6: I am a lover of baking pies and reading any auto-bio I can get my hands on. 

7: My husband and I will celebrate 10 years of marriage next year and it didn’t come easy. We have a fun announcement in the next couple weeks of a new endeavor we’re doing together! 

8: While grateful for a music career spanning decades, my main goal in life is to help people find freedom. Within that, owning their own stories no matter how messy they are, and forgiving themselves for the things they weren’t equipped to handle. 

9: I still write songs and sing….as well as occasionally traveling with my husband to lead at worship events. I am finally writing a memoir of sorts and that will be released next year!! 

10: For the time, we are residing in Nashville with our daughter while our two adult kids take over the world. We are also the proud parents of a puppy named Rocky.
Happy Monday, friends! ❤️

“Winds in the east, mist coming in, Like somethin' is brewin' and bout to begin. Can’t put my finger on what lies in store, But I fear what's to happen all happened before.” 

Here we go….

When life from within you exhales a first breath on this side of earth, the holiest of moments takes over and shifts the foundations of everything you’ve ever thought, felt, or believed. 
All fear of how this will transpire and if you’ll be able to arise to the calling, fade as the spirit within you suddenly knows that protecting this gift, is as natural as being who you have always been. 
Their joy becomes your joy.
Their pain becomes your pain. 
Their beauty becomes your delight. 
As you embark on an unknown adventure, you realize that who they are, has nothing to do with you. 
Sure, you can influence and share your ideas, try to mold and shape something that flows with the pace of your own stream…but eventually, they begin to venture into places out of reach. 
You then become a witness to a soul finding their purpose. 
The Love within yourself becomes too much to contain or manage…
You react. 
You grasp.
You fear. 
You reach. 
And a culmination of thoughts, play like a movie in your head. 
The rounding of syllables into her first words. 
The strength of her legs as she grounds herself into the floor to stand, to reach out for you.
The view of her outstretched arms, etch into my heart, as I’m reminded of the steps towards me as she longed for the payoff of my embrace at the end of her first walk. 
And one day, when time has created distance from the purest moments of watching the journey of the one who holds your heart….
You stand up with your feet grounded, and you walk towards them, reaching. 

I’m in awe of who you are. 
I’m in awe of who you are becoming. 
I’m in awe of how you’ve overcome. 
I’m in awe of how you’ve survived. 

The depths you’ve reached within yourself to attain understanding. 
The way you’ve fought to stay authentic. 
The way you teach. 
The way you love. 

You are the greatest thing to happen to my life. 
You shifted the trajectory of my future into the greatest adventure I could ever have. 

I can’t believe I get to be your mother forever. 

On this day, 23 years ago, I wept tears onto your perfect little body, and nothing else mattered. 

Thank you for always being you. I love you with everything I have.

Happy Thanksgiving, Everyone!

My family has so much to be thankful for this year. Here’s the wild part, we’ve actually had more opposition and more mind-blowing circumstances than most years. However, we decided to count it all joy and just start trusting God in ways that we never have before. There’s something so profound that happens when you just release the grip of obsession that comes with wanting immediate resolution of things that take time. 

We’ve been more committed than ever before to not wasting time in worry and trusting the process. 

This year, I’m thankful for peace. I’m thankful for release. I’m thankful for laughter when all you can do is just laugh about the absurdity of what life can throw your way. I’m thankful for the journey, the growth, and the very hard road to finding myself outside of what i do. 

God is good! 

📸: @madison_watkins
